<DOC><DOCNO> AP880503-0272 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1955EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-SouthKorea-US     05-03 0266</FIRST><SECOND>BC-South Korea-US,0276</SECOND><HEAD>U.S. Presses For South Korea To Remove Import Barriers</HEAD><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The United States Tuesday asked SouthKorea to protect American intellectual property rights and liftsales restrictions on foreign cigarettes, government officials said.   In the second day of a scheduled three-day trade meeting whichopened in Seoul on Monday, the United States also asked South Koreato open its advertising and insurance markets, the officials said.   ``The meeting was very useful. There were detailed discussionson almost all pending issues,'' a South Korean official said afterTuesday's talks.   The 19-member U.S. delegation, headed by Peter Allgier,assistant chief of the U.S. Trade Representative Office, demandedthat South Korea protect 911 U.S. chemical products which arepatented but not marketed, retroactive to Jan. 1, 1987, theofficials said.   South Korea promised to reply to the U.S. request before theSeoul meeting ends on Wednesday, they said.   U.S. officials also called for the South Korean government totighten control on pirated books under a 1985 agreement, in whichSeoul officials promised to protect the U.S. copyrights, theofficials said.   The United States took a critical stand on South Korea'scigarette sales system and demanded that the prices of importedforeign cigarettes be lowered to the level of domestic brands, theysaid.   Imported American cigarettes sell for $1.76 a pack compared with81 cents a pack for the most expensive local brand.   The United States also asked South Korea to permit cigaretteadvertisements through all news media, but South Korea said theadvertisements would be limited to magazines, the officials said.</TEXT></DOC>